0
00:00:01,000 --> 00:00:04,000
Downloaded From www.AllSubs.org

1
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:43,923
Enjoying that, are you, sir?

2
00:00:44,097 --> 00:00:47,472
Sergeant, my wife is
currently taking a course

3
00:00:47,646 --> 00:00:50,011
at the Continental School
of Gourmet Cooking.

4
00:00:50,185 --> 00:00:52,865
Apparently they don't know the principle:
To eat well in this country,

5
00:00:53,038 --> 00:00:55,404
one must have breakfast
three times a day.

6
00:00:55,578 --> 00:00:58,710
And an English breakfast at that.
I don't mean your <i>café complet.</i>

7
00:00:58,884 --> 00:01:01,946
- Beg pardon, sir?
- A cup of coffee half an inch deep,

8
00:01:02,120 --> 00:01:05,460
in floating bits of boiled milk,
and a sweet bun full of air.

9
00:01:05,634 --> 00:01:07,930
- That's what I had this morning.
- I see what you mean, sir.

10
00:01:08,104 --> 00:01:10,992
- I'm a... Quaker Oats man, myself.
- (Chuckles)

11
00:01:11,166 --> 00:01:12,627
<i>(Knock At Door)</i>

12
00:01:13,845 --> 00:01:15,515
Excuse me, sir.

13
00:01:15,689 --> 00:01:18,751
This has just come in.
It's the lab report on the ten-pound note

14
00:01:18,925 --> 00:01:21,778
- that Blaney paid the hotel bill with.
- Yes.

15
00:01:21,952 --> 00:01:25,014
As you'll see, the note
bore traces of face powder

16
00:01:25,188 --> 00:01:27,658
identical to that which we found
in Mrs Blaney's handbag.

17
00:01:27,832 --> 00:01:30,615
- Thank you.
- Thank you, sir.

18
00:01:30,789 --> 00:01:33,155
Well, Sergeant, we were in luck after all.

19
00:01:33,329 --> 00:01:37,365
- That just about does it for him.
- Looks very much like it.

20
00:01:37,539 --> 00:01:42,654
I've never run into any of these
jokers before. What are they like?

21
00:01:42,828 --> 00:01:45,333
Oh, they vary, but not a lot.

22
00:01:45,507 --> 00:01:48,464
The thing to remember is they hate
women, and are mostly impotent.

23
00:01:48,638 --> 00:01:54,170
- Impotent?
- Don't mistake rape for potency.

24
00:01:54,344 --> 00:01:55,736
In the latter stage of the disease,

25
00:01:55,875 --> 00:01:59,320
it's the strangling, not the sex,
that brings them on.

26
00:01:59,459 --> 00:02:01,686
Above all, of course, they're sadists.

27
00:02:01,860 --> 00:02:04,295
- You know what they are, I'm sure.
- Oh, yes, sir.

28
00:02:04,469 --> 00:02:08,470
If you don't, read all about it in here:
Mrs Blaney's divorce petition.

29
00:02:08,644 --> 00:02:11,184
It tells you a great deal
about the habits of our hero.

30
00:02:11,358 --> 00:02:13,446
<i>(Phone Ringing)</i>

31
00:02:13,620 --> 00:02:15,533
Yeah?

32
00:02:15,707 --> 00:02:19,396
Right. Put him on.
Yes, Chief Inspector Oxford speaking.

33
00:02:19,570 --> 00:02:23,118
My name is Forsythe, Inspector. Felix Forsythe.

34
00:02:23,292 --> 00:02:25,658
I run the Globe Public House, Covent Garden.

35
00:02:25,832 --> 00:02:29,242
I see from the newspaper you're
in charge of these strangling cases.

36
00:02:29,416 --> 00:02:30,843
Yes, that is so.

37
00:02:31,017 --> 00:02:33,696
Good, because I've got
some information to impart.

38
00:02:33,870 --> 00:02:38,671
Now, this man you're looking for,
the one with the patches on his suit.

39
00:02:38,845 --> 00:02:41,802
I know him. He worked here as a barman.

40
00:02:41,976 --> 00:02:45,491
His name is Richard Blaney.
He's a right bastard.

41
00:02:45,665 --> 00:02:50,396
Are you quite certain it's the same man?

42
00:02:50,570 --> 00:02:53,354
Gone off with your barmaid?
What exactly do you mean by gone off?

43
00:02:53,528 --> 00:02:55,789
She's been out all night with him
and hasn't yet returned.

44
00:02:55,963 --> 00:03:00,417
I felt it my duty to tell you that
I consider her to be in great danger.

45
00:03:00,591 --> 00:03:02,122
That is, of course,
if she's still alive and kicking.

46
00:03:02,296 --> 00:03:04,349
Thank you for your information, Mr Forsythe.

47
00:03:04,557 --> 00:03:08,071
Tell me, what does this
barmaid of yours look like?

48
00:03:13,464 --> 00:03:17,779
I can set your mind at rest.
She was alive at 8:00 this morning.

49
00:03:17,918 --> 00:03:20,006
8:00 this morning?

50
00:03:20,180 --> 00:03:22,893
Well, where is she now? We opened at 11:00!

51
00:03:23,067 --> 00:03:27,277
But is she coming back here or not?
She's left all her clothes!

52
00:03:27,451 --> 00:03:29,226
I expect she'll turn up.

53
00:03:29,400 --> 00:03:32,636
Today, ladies abandon their honour
more readily than their clothes.

54
00:03:32,810 --> 00:03:36,498
Thank you for your information,
Mr Forsythe. I'll send someone over.

55
00:03:36,672 --> 00:03:40,429
That was Forsythe, manager of
the Globe Pub, Covent Garden.

56
00:03:46,553 --> 00:03:49,302
I tell you what, Jim,
I'm glad I'm not in the potato business.

57
00:03:49,476 --> 00:03:52,990
- Got enough troubles of me own.
- You're not a bad judge, Bob.

58
00:03:53,164 --> 00:03:55,669
The potato business is poison, always was.

59
00:03:55,843 --> 00:03:59,044
It costs a fortune to dig 'em up,
another fortune to transport them.

60
00:03:59,218 --> 00:04:02,627
<i>And what do you have at the end?</i>
<i>Hardly any money for them.</i>

61
00:04:02,801 --> 00:04:04,471
Mostly you can't sell them.

62
00:04:04,645 --> 00:04:07,498
I've got to send a truckload
back up to Lincolnshire tonight.

63
00:04:07,638 --> 00:04:11,221
And what will they do with them?
They'll plow them back in.

64
00:04:11,395 --> 00:04:13,065
<i>(Jim) Can you beat it?</i>

65
00:04:13,239 --> 00:04:14,909
<i>And they say</i>
<i>there's people hungry in this world.</i>

66
00:04:15,083 --> 00:04:17,658
<i>True, Jim.</i>
<i>And there are a few thirsty as well.</i>

67
00:04:17,832 --> 00:04:20,302
<i>Come on, have one with your Uncle Bob.</i>

68
00:04:22,494 --> 00:04:24,373
<i>Good afternoon!</i>

69
00:04:24,547 --> 00:04:28,757
Where do you think you've been?
Your half-day was yesterday!

70
00:04:28,931 --> 00:04:32,515
You took a hell of a chance,
spending the night with a murderer.

71
00:04:32,689 --> 00:04:34,707
- How do you know what I did?
- Now come off it.

72
00:04:34,881 --> 00:04:36,934
You took his clothes.
You didn't come home. It stands to reason.

73
00:04:37,108 --> 00:04:40,483
- Mind your own bleeding business!
- Don't talk to me like that!

74
00:04:40,657 --> 00:04:44,553
I was worried you might be next.
I even phoned the police.

75
00:04:44,727 --> 00:04:45,771
- Police?
- Yeah. They wanna talk to you.

76
00:04:45,945 --> 00:04:48,102
- They're sending a fella over.
- Why?

77
00:04:48,276 --> 00:04:49,564
Why? Because they want your lover.

78
00:04:49,738 --> 00:04:53,008
They wanna put him where he can't
strangle any more women!

79
00:04:53,182 --> 00:04:55,861
And you'd better help 'em.
The sooner he's behind bars the better.

80
00:04:56,035 --> 00:04:57,705
Don't you talk about him like that!

81
00:04:57,879 --> 00:05:00,558
You don't realise how lucky
you are to be alive!

82
00:05:00,732 --> 00:05:04,455
Christ Almighty, Babs, if I wasn't
shorthanded, I'd take you myself!

83
00:05:04,629 --> 00:05:07,795
- As it is, right after closing time -
- I won't be here!

84
00:05:07,969 --> 00:05:09,048
<i>You can stuff your rotten job</i>
<i>right up your jacksie!</i>

85
00:05:09,117 --> 00:05:10,335
<i>- Come back, you!</i>
- Oh, balls!

86
00:05:18,651 --> 00:05:20,251
Got a place to stay?

87
00:05:20,425 --> 00:05:23,452
<i>- Oh, it's you, Bob.</i>
- Yeah.

88
00:05:23,591 --> 00:05:26,792
- I heard you argue with Forsythe.
- Oh, he's a right bastard.

89
00:05:26,966 --> 00:05:29,054
Of course he is.

90
00:05:35,734 --> 00:05:39,875
You can stay at my place 'til you get
something sorted out... if you want.

91
00:05:40,049 --> 00:05:42,623
I won't be in your way.
I'm going up north for a few days.

92
00:05:42,797 --> 00:05:45,720
- No strings?
- Do I look like that sort of a bloke?

93
00:05:45,894 --> 00:05:49,234
All blokes are that sort of a bloke.

94
00:05:49,408 --> 00:05:52,087
- Are you really goin' away?
- Sure! Tonight.

95
00:05:52,261 --> 00:05:55,219
You can have the place to yourself.
I'll take you there now.

96
00:05:55,393 --> 00:05:58,106
If you like, I'll go back to the Globe
and pick up your stuff for you.

97
00:05:58,280 --> 00:06:00,403
Now, I can't say fairer than that, can I?

98
00:06:00,577 --> 00:06:03,465
Oh, thanks, Bob. I'll just stay
the one night if you don't mind.

99
00:06:03,639 --> 00:06:06,770
- Suit yourself
- Tomorrow, I'm gonna go to, um...

100
00:06:06,944 --> 00:06:09,693
I'm going to my sister in Southall.

101
00:06:09,867 --> 00:06:11,745
Leaving your boyfriend
in the lurch a bit, aren't you?

102
00:06:11,919 --> 00:06:14,077
He has to make up
his own mind what to do.

103
00:06:14,251 --> 00:06:17,417
I'd like to help him if I could.
Where's he hiding out?

104
00:06:17,591 --> 00:06:19,713
- Can't tell you, Bob. I promised.
- Ohh!

105
00:06:19,887 --> 00:06:23,332
Come on, Babs. Dick and me have
always been mates. You know that.

106
00:06:23,506 --> 00:06:25,210
I can't.

107
00:06:25,384 --> 00:06:29,316
Alright. Keep your little secret.

108
00:06:29,490 --> 00:06:33,978
Changing jobs can be a blessing in disguise.
It gets you out of a rut.

109
00:06:34,152 --> 00:06:37,319
A girl like you ought to travel,
see the world a bit.

110
00:06:37,458 --> 00:06:40,763
The Cape, California, Jaffa.
Where the fruit comes from,

111
00:06:40,937 --> 00:06:43,303
that's where I'd like to go
if I wasn't tied down here.

112
00:06:43,477 --> 00:06:45,808
But you, you can do as you please!

113
00:06:45,982 --> 00:06:49,218
You've got the whole
of your life ahead of you.

114
00:06:51,793 --> 00:06:54,402
Here we are. I'm on the second floor.

115
00:07:13,817 --> 00:07:16,600
I don't know if you know it, Babs,

116
00:07:16,774 --> 00:07:20,045
<i>but you're my type of woman.</i>

117
00:07:55,986 --> 00:07:58,039
<i>(Footsteps, Cars Passing)</i>

118
00:08:23,543 --> 00:08:26,813
<i>- (Mrs Oxford) Is that you, Tim?</i>
- Hello, dear.

119
00:08:26,987 --> 00:08:29,771
<i>- Hungry?</i>
- Yes!

120
00:08:29,910 --> 00:08:32,728
Good. I'll bring it right in.

121
00:08:35,129 --> 00:08:38,295
It's a soupe de poisson, dear.

122
00:08:38,469 --> 00:08:41,809
<i>- l know you'll enjoy it.</i>
- I have no doubt of it.

123
00:08:42,366 --> 00:08:45,462
Don't wait for me. I'm just going
to see to the next course.

124
00:08:49,116 --> 00:08:53,952
Well... what's new in the case?
Any sensational breaks?

125
00:08:54,126 --> 00:08:59,032
No. I'll be glad when we get
Mr Richard Blaney inside, though.

126
00:08:59,206 --> 00:09:01,989
Any idea where he is?

127
00:09:04,112 --> 00:09:07,313
No, our only lead to him
left her job this morning.

128
00:09:07,521 --> 00:09:11,905
<i>- l don't know where she is either.</i>
- You're certain he's the one?

129
00:09:12,079 --> 00:09:14,584
Oh, yes, he's... the one, alright.

130
00:09:14,758 --> 00:09:16,881
There's not even the complication
of another suspect.

131
00:09:17,055 --> 00:09:19,142
<i>It has to be him.</i>

132
00:09:24,257 --> 00:09:27,214
We have him identified as leaving
the matrimonial agency

133
00:09:27,388 --> 00:09:30,102
at the time his ex was killed.

134
00:09:30,276 --> 00:09:34,625
We have the clothes which he sent
off to the cleaners in a hurry.

135
00:09:34,799 --> 00:09:37,548
And we have the evidence of the face powder

136
00:09:37,687 --> 00:09:39,079
and the Salvation Army hostel.

137
00:09:39,879 --> 00:09:41,758
I don't follow you, my dear.

138
00:09:41,932 --> 00:09:44,820
I didn't think the Salvation Army
girls used makeup.

139
00:09:46,003 --> 00:09:50,630
No, Blaney slept in a Salvation Army
hostel the night before last.

140
00:09:50,804 --> 00:09:52,892
<i>- Did he, dear?</i>
- Yes.

141
00:09:56,058 --> 00:09:59,016
He was incautious enough
to tell them his name.

142
00:09:59,190 --> 00:10:01,660
I don't think an ex-RAF officer
would sleep in such a place

143
00:10:01,869 --> 00:10:04,965
- unless he was broke, do you?
<i>- No, l don't.</i>

144
00:10:05,139 --> 00:10:08,027
So, let's assume he was.

145
00:10:09,210 --> 00:10:12,237
Last night, however, he slept in the...

146
00:10:12,411 --> 00:10:13,907
Coburg Hotel in Bayswater,

147
00:10:14,081 --> 00:10:18,778
and paid for his extremely expensive
room with a ten-pound note.

148
00:10:19,578 --> 00:10:22,710
The note bore traces
of Mrs Blaney's face powder.

149
00:10:22,884 --> 00:10:25,841
I mean, the murderer
not only strangled Mrs Blaney,

150
00:10:26,015 --> 00:10:28,068
he stole money from her handbag as well.

151
00:10:28,242 --> 00:10:33,426
Ergo... Blaney is the thief
and also the murderer.

152
00:10:34,470 --> 00:10:36,314
That ties it up then.

153
00:10:36,488 --> 00:10:39,063
Well, I think so.

154
00:10:40,280 --> 00:10:42,820
And furthermore, there is a waitress

155
00:10:42,994 --> 00:10:45,117
at Mrs Blaney's club who can also testify

156
00:10:45,291 --> 00:10:48,526
to Blaney's aggressive behaviour
towards his wife the previous night.

157
00:10:49,953 --> 00:10:52,562
He doesn't seem to have been
very discreet, does he?

158
00:10:52,736 --> 00:10:56,425
No. Discretion is not traditionally
the strong suit of the psychopath.

159
00:10:56,633 --> 00:10:58,338
Believe me, that's what we're dealing with.

160
00:10:58,512 --> 00:11:01,156
You ought to read his wife's divorce...
petition.

161
00:11:01,330 --> 00:11:03,244
What exactly is in this soup?

162
00:11:03,418 --> 00:11:05,506
Why? Don't you like it?

163
00:11:05,680 --> 00:11:10,342
Mmm! It's delicious.

164
00:11:10,516 --> 00:11:12,047
But I find the...

165
00:11:12,221 --> 00:11:15,596
ingredients somewhat mystifying.

166
00:11:15,770 --> 00:11:18,379
They're smelts, ling,

167
00:11:18,553 --> 00:11:20,919
conger eel, John Dory,

168
00:11:21,093 --> 00:11:24,294
pilchards and frog fish.

169
00:11:25,442 --> 00:11:27,808
Now, since that must've been
fairly satisfying,

170
00:11:27,982 --> 00:11:32,018
I thought a simple
roast bird would be enough.

171
00:11:36,402 --> 00:11:38,803
<i>Caille aux raisins.</i>

172
00:11:39,568 --> 00:11:40,612
Hmm?

173
00:11:40,995 --> 00:11:45,240
Quail with... grapes.

174
00:11:45,414 --> 00:11:47,501
Ahh!

175
00:11:51,328 --> 00:11:54,773
- I must say, I'm very worried.
- About Mr Blaney?

176
00:11:54,947 --> 00:11:58,357
<i>Yes. He's gone off with a barmaid</i>
<i>he used to work with.</i>

177
00:11:58,531 --> 00:12:01,766
<i>l think she's in very great danger.</i>

178
00:12:01,940 --> 00:12:05,107
You're wrong, Tim. Absolutely wrong.

179
00:12:05,281 --> 00:12:07,507
<i>It can't be this fellow.</i>

180
00:12:07,681 --> 00:12:09,525
<i>How long did you say he was married?</i>

181
00:12:09,699 --> 00:12:11,648
Ten years.

182
00:12:11,822 --> 00:12:13,770
Well... there you are.

183
00:12:13,944 --> 00:12:18,119
A crime de passion after all that time?

184
00:12:18,293 --> 00:12:21,703
Look at us. We've only been married
eight years,

185
00:12:21,877 --> 00:12:25,287
and you can hardly keep
your eyes open at night.

186
00:12:25,461 --> 00:12:27,653
That's as may be,
but I don't knock you about,

187
00:12:27,827 --> 00:12:30,541
or make you do degrading things.

188
00:12:30,714 --> 00:12:33,115
No, the evidence speaks for itself.

189
00:12:33,289 --> 00:12:37,395
You can't make normal judgments
about psychopathic killers.

190
00:12:37,569 --> 00:12:39,378
They can be triggered off at any time.

191
00:12:39,552 --> 00:12:44,945
We've got to find him before his...
appetite is whetted again.

192
00:13:14,554 --> 00:13:16,642
<i>(Clock Chiming)</i>

193
00:13:27,219 --> 00:13:29,306
<i>(Clock Strikes 1:00)</i>

194
00:13:36,335 --> 00:13:38,388
(Grunting)

195
00:14:33,987 --> 00:14:36,040
<i>(Men Laughing)</i>

196
00:16:58,171 --> 00:17:00,224
Christ all-bloody-mighty!

197
00:17:51,544 --> 00:17:53,910
<i>(Man) See you, mate.</i>

198
00:17:55,754 --> 00:17:57,459
<i>(Footsteps)</i>

199
00:18:04,731 --> 00:18:06,609
<i>(Truck Door Closes)</i>

200
00:18:06,783 --> 00:18:08,836
<i>(Engine Starts)</i>

201
00:19:55,547 --> 00:19:57,635
(Coughing)

202
00:20:01,114 --> 00:20:03,793
# (Whistling)

203
00:20:06,403 --> 00:20:08,490
Ah... Ah...

204
00:20:12,039 --> 00:20:14,092
(Muffled Sneeze)

205
00:20:26,548 --> 00:20:29,297
You bitch! Where's that bloody pin?

206
00:20:29,471 --> 00:20:31,558
# (Whistling)

207
00:20:34,446 --> 00:20:36,499
<i>(Brakes Squeal)</i>

208
00:20:51,495 --> 00:20:53,931
Hey, you're spilling your load!

209
00:20:54,105 --> 00:20:57,793
- What?
- The potatoes are falling out.

210
