<i>(Truck Shifting Gears)</i>

214
00:24:15,593 --> 00:24:17,576
# <i>(Music From Inside Cafe)</i>

215
00:24:21,473 --> 00:24:23,526
<i>(Footsteps)</i>

216
00:24:48,264 --> 00:24:49,655
(Indistinct Chatter)

217
00:25:50,787 --> 00:25:52,875
Hey, do you see what I see?

218
00:26:07,488 --> 00:26:09,576
<i>(Siren Wailing)</i>

219
00:26:17,195 --> 00:26:19,283
(Tyres Screeching)

220
00:26:25,163 --> 00:26:30,139
- Here, what's wrong... Who is it?
<i>- (Policeman) Perhaps you can tell us.</i>

221
00:26:32,887 --> 00:26:34,140
<i>- Wake up!</i>
- What?

222
00:26:34,314 --> 00:26:35,636
<i>- Get out of here!</i>
- What is it?

223
00:26:35,810 --> 00:26:39,080
Brenda wasn't enough for you.
You had to kill another girl too!

224
00:26:39,254 --> 00:26:42,699
- What girl?
- That girl you were with yesterday.

225
00:26:42,873 --> 00:26:46,074
- Babs?
- As if you didn't know.

226
00:26:46,248 --> 00:26:49,275
You strangled her like all the others!

227
00:26:49,449 --> 00:26:51,258
She's been strangled?

228
00:26:51,467 --> 00:26:55,607
Don't you playact with me.
Get up and get out of here.

229
00:26:55,781 --> 00:26:58,286
I'd call the police myself if I knew
how to without getting involved.

230
00:26:58,460 --> 00:27:01,835
I don't believe it. I just don't believe it.

231
00:27:02,009 --> 00:27:04,723
It's true, Dicko. It just came over on the radio.

232
00:27:04,897 --> 00:27:07,576
They found her in a potato truck
in Lincolnshire.

233
00:27:07,750 --> 00:27:09,594
The fellow at the pub
where you worked identified her.

234
00:27:09,768 --> 00:27:12,586
He knows where they found her.
He put her there!

235
00:27:12,760 --> 00:27:14,918
What are you talking about?
I haven't left this room all night.

236
00:27:15,092 --> 00:27:16,692
Liar. I don't believe you.

237
00:27:16,866 --> 00:27:19,476
It doesn't matter whether
you believe him or not,

238
00:27:19,649 --> 00:27:22,503
because it said on the radio she had
been dead for at least 12 hours

239
00:27:22,676 --> 00:27:24,590
when they found her at 3:00 this morning.

240
00:27:24,764 --> 00:27:28,139
She must've been killed
before 3:00 yesterday afternoon.

241
00:27:28,313 --> 00:27:30,714
Dick was with us from the time
she left to the time we went to bed.

242
00:27:30,923 --> 00:27:33,602
So he couldn't have done it.

243
00:27:33,776 --> 00:27:36,420
- Poor kid.
<i>- (Hetty) l still don't believe it.</i>

244
00:27:36,594 --> 00:27:38,716
They're only guessing when she was killed.

245
00:27:38,890 --> 00:27:41,639
We didn't go to bed 'til 11:00,
and Dick was here with us then.

246
00:27:41,778 --> 00:27:45,362
They can't be eight hours adrift. Dicko?

247
00:27:45,536 --> 00:27:50,476
<i>Don't you see? You're in the clear!</i>
<i>We can give you an alibi.</i>

248
00:27:50,650 --> 00:27:52,808
Yes. Yes, I suppose you can.

249
00:27:52,981 --> 00:27:56,322
There's no supposing. We'll simply
tell the police you were here with us.

250
00:27:56,461 --> 00:27:58,792
Would you do that? Would you do it
now before you go away?

251
00:27:58,966 --> 00:28:03,767
- Of course I would. Delighted.
- You'll do no such thing!

252
00:28:03,941 --> 00:28:06,133
Not unless you want to go to jail
for harboring a wanted man.

253
00:28:06,307 --> 00:28:08,812
<i>- But he's not a criminal.</i>
<i>- The police think he is!</i>

254
00:28:08,986 --> 00:28:10,378
And they have a lot of evidence against him.

255
00:28:10,517 --> 00:28:13,857
We know he didn't kill her.
We must tell them he was with us.

256
00:28:14,031 --> 00:28:16,397
But we don't know he didn't kill Miss Milligan!

257
00:28:16,571 --> 00:28:19,285
For all we know the time given
on the radio might've been a trap.

258
00:28:19,459 --> 00:28:22,243
<i>What is certain, if you go to the police,</i>

259
00:28:22,417 --> 00:28:25,409
they will probably charge you with
being an accessory after the fact.

260
00:28:25,583 --> 00:28:26,975
And they certainly
won't allow us to go abroad,

261
00:28:27,149 --> 00:28:29,793
and they will probably put us in jail.

262
00:28:37,134 --> 00:28:42,214
Well, Hetty's right, dammit.
You can see that, Dicko, can't you?

263
00:28:42,388 --> 00:28:44,476
You mean you won't come
to the police with me?

264
00:28:44,650 --> 00:28:48,094
- How can I? You heard Hetty.
- You're my only alibi!

265
00:28:48,268 --> 00:28:51,747
I'm sorry. I've got to get to Paris today.
I can't afford to be kept here.

266
00:28:51,921 --> 00:28:54,183
But you can afford to stand by
and see me go to jail for life!

267
00:28:54,357 --> 00:28:55,957
<i>- Is that it?</i>
- It's not as bad as that.

268
00:28:56,131 --> 00:28:58,045
I mean, they'll find this strangler chappie.

269
00:28:58,219 --> 00:28:59,680
Of all the cowardly shits!

270
00:28:59,819 --> 00:29:02,742
<i>It's I'm alright Jack,</i>
<i>and haul up the ladder, isn't it?</i>

271
00:29:02,916 --> 00:29:05,004
You pair of bastards!

272
00:29:05,178 --> 00:29:08,309
If that's how you feel after all we've
done for you, you better had go!

273
00:29:08,483 --> 00:29:10,257
I'll call the manager.

274
00:29:10,431 --> 00:29:13,876
And involve yourself? Don't worry, I'm going.

275
00:29:14,050 --> 00:29:18,504
I'm a little choosy with whom
I spend my last hours of freedom.

276
00:29:18,677 --> 00:29:23,131
Look, I'm sorry. I'd suggest that you
came to Paris and worked in a pub,

277
00:29:23,305 --> 00:29:26,471
but they're watching all the ports
and stations. It said so on the news.

278
00:29:26,645 --> 00:29:28,942
Well, that lets you out then, doesn't it?

279
00:29:29,115 --> 00:29:31,203
Your responsibility for me ends here.

280
00:29:35,970 --> 00:29:39,171
<i>Clear this area, please. Thank you, madam.</i>
<i>Stand back, please.</i>

281
00:29:42,059 --> 00:29:44,425
Looks as though we've got half
the law in London in the market.

282
00:29:44,599 --> 00:29:48,287
Yeah. It makes it very difficult
to give short weight.

283
00:29:48,461 --> 00:29:49,504
I suppose they're trying to find out

284
00:29:49,678 --> 00:29:53,192
if anybody saw Blaney put
Babs on that potato truck.

285
00:29:53,332 --> 00:29:56,393
- You think he did it, do you?
- It stands to reason, doesn't it?

286
00:29:56,567 --> 00:29:57,576
Why? Don't you?

287
00:29:57,785 --> 00:30:00,638
I'm not as eager as some
to turn on my old mates.

288
00:30:00,812 --> 00:30:03,422
What are you talkin' about?
Blaney wasn't a mate of mine.

289
00:30:03,596 --> 00:30:05,753
- I had to sack him for stealin'.
- Get off.

290
00:30:05,962 --> 00:30:08,710
Yeah, Blaney was a thief, right bastard.

291
00:30:08,849 --> 00:30:11,981
I even told that Chief Inspector,
but he didn't believe a word, did he?

292
00:30:12,155 --> 00:30:14,242
I expect he's laughing
on the other side of his face now.

293
00:30:14,416 --> 00:30:17,026
- You reckon?
- Yeah, definitely, definitely.

294
00:30:17,200 --> 00:30:20,470
He wasn't so cocky
when I saw him at 7:00 this morning.

295
00:30:20,610 --> 00:30:23,324
I've just been down
to Scotland Yard to identify her.

296
00:30:23,497 --> 00:30:28,369
From photos. They took 'em
and they rushed 'em down special.

297
00:30:28,543 --> 00:30:32,300
- She wasn't a pretty sight.
- Some people have all the luck.

298
00:30:32,474 --> 00:30:34,005
Yeah. I better get a move on.

299
00:30:34,179 --> 00:30:37,519
Business will be pretty brisk today.
You know how morbid people are.

300
00:30:37,693 --> 00:30:41,068
Absolutely! Jumping up to identify
dead girls at all hours of the night.

301
00:30:41,242 --> 00:30:43,295
See you later.

302
00:30:48,688 --> 00:30:50,775
My God, Dick!

303
00:30:53,420 --> 00:30:55,473
Whatcha doin' here?

304
00:30:55,647 --> 00:30:57,943
I'm sorry, Bob,
but I had nowhere else to go.

305
00:30:58,117 --> 00:31:00,587
The people I was staying
with left for Paris this morning.

306
00:31:00,761 --> 00:31:04,449
I wouldn't have come, but you did
say if I needed anything, anytime...

307
00:31:04,623 --> 00:31:08,137
Yes, of course! But you took a hell
of a chance coming here today.

308
00:31:08,311 --> 00:31:11,756
The whole place is teeming with coppers.
Wait a minute.

309
00:31:15,861 --> 00:31:19,897
You'd better hole up in my place for
a day or two 'til we sort something.

310
00:31:20,071 --> 00:31:22,994
Yes. I thought maybe if you had the room.

311
00:31:23,133 --> 00:31:25,952
I know it's a hell of an imposition
getting you involved and everything.

312
00:31:26,125 --> 00:31:29,466
<i>You've got to believe me.</i>
<i>l haven't murdered anyone!</i>

313
00:31:29,674 --> 00:31:32,562
This whole business is insane! You know me.

314
00:31:32,736 --> 00:31:37,120
<i>- l wouldn't do anything like this.</i>
- Of course you wouldn't. No.

315
00:31:37,294 --> 00:31:41,748
The police, as usual, have got
the whole thing arse about face.

316
00:31:41,922 --> 00:31:44,914
I mean, these sort of killings
always boggle the mind.

317
00:31:45,088 --> 00:31:48,498
That man must be a sexual maniac.

318
00:31:49,715 --> 00:31:54,482
Mind you, there are some women
who ask for everything they get.

319
00:31:54,656 --> 00:31:57,857
But you? Don't make me laugh.
You're not the type.

320
00:31:58,031 --> 00:32:00,084
Now... don't worry.

321
00:32:00,258 --> 00:32:04,224
<i>You've done the right thing</i>
<i>coming to your Uncle Bob.</i>

322
00:32:04,398 --> 00:32:07,112
Right. Well, let's get over to
my place. You know where it is?

323
00:32:07,286 --> 00:32:09,687
- Yeah.
- I'll go first, and I'll take the bag.

324
00:32:09,861 --> 00:32:11,948
- Then you'll be less conspicuous .
- OK.

325
00:32:12,122 --> 00:32:14,836
You follow, but go the long way.
Go down to the Strand, you know.

326
00:32:15,010 --> 00:32:17,202
And then work your way up
Southampton Street. OK?

327
00:32:17,376 --> 00:32:19,464
Yeah.

328
00:33:42,028 --> 00:33:44,847
Well done, boy! Come in.

329
00:33:45,020 --> 00:33:47,386
Make yourself comfortable.

330
00:33:47,560 --> 00:33:51,179
- Very cozy.
- Yes, well, it's my little nest.

331
00:33:51,353 --> 00:33:53,440
You know, my home.

332
00:33:53,614 --> 00:33:55,876
The place where when you have
to go there, they have to take you in.

333
00:33:56,050 --> 00:33:59,007
That's what my ol' mum used to say.
You met my mum, didn't you?

334
00:33:59,181 --> 00:34:02,974
- Yes.
<i>- Ah, great old lady.</i>

335
00:34:03,148 --> 00:34:06,592
- I'm off to the shop. See you later!
<i>- Yeah, sure.</i>

336
00:34:06,766 --> 00:34:08,854
There's something to eat in the kitchen.
The booze is here.

337
00:34:09,028 --> 00:34:11,115
<i>So get on with it, right?</i>

338
00:34:11,289 --> 00:34:15,186
Bob, I'm really grateful for all this.
You know that.

339
00:34:15,360 --> 00:34:17,517
<i>l told you, think nothing of it.</i>

340
00:34:17,691 --> 00:34:19,744
Hey, do me a favour, will you?

341
00:34:19,918 --> 00:34:23,293
<i>- Keep away from the windows.</i>
- Yes, of course. Sorry.

342
00:34:23,467 --> 00:34:25,242
Ta-ta.

343
00:34:25,416 --> 00:34:27,573
Don't do anything I wouldn't do.

344
00:34:57,425 --> 00:34:59,478
<i>(Door Opens)</i>

345
00:34:59,652 --> 00:35:01,322
Are you Richard Ian Blaney?

346
00:35:01,496 --> 00:35:03,584
- Yes. What is this?
- You're under arrest.

347
00:35:03,758 --> 00:35:04,802
Come quietly, and you won't get hurt.

348
00:35:04,976 --> 00:35:07,585
- Is this necessary?
- We're careful with you bastards.

349
00:35:07,759 --> 00:35:09,394
- Is this your bag?
- Yes.

350
00:35:25,782 --> 00:35:29,957
-Thank you for your help, Mr Rusk.
- Anything to oblige, Sarge.

351
00:35:30,131 --> 00:35:32,741
No reward, I'm afraid.
Better luck next time, eh?

352
00:35:32,915 --> 00:35:35,907
You know what they say.
Virtue is its own reward.

353
00:35:36,081 --> 00:35:40,152
I... Well, if you want any more help,
I'll be in my shop.

354
00:35:40,326 --> 00:35:42,170
Alright. We know where you are.

355
00:35:47,806 --> 00:35:51,425
How's that kid of yours
gettin' on with the violin?

356
00:35:58,592 --> 00:36:01,341
- Richard Ian Blaney?
- Yes.

357
00:36:01,515 --> 00:36:04,403
As the result of my inquiries,
you'll be detained in connection

358
00:36:04,577 --> 00:36:06,803
with the willful murders
of Brenda Margaret Blaney,

359
00:36:06,977 --> 00:36:09,448
Barbara Jane Milligan and others.

360
00:36:09,622 --> 00:36:11,431
You're not obliged to say anything
unless you wish.

361
00:36:11,605 --> 00:36:13,762
Anything you do say will be
taken down in writing

362
00:36:13,971 --> 00:36:15,328
and may be used in evidence.

363
00:36:15,502 --> 00:36:18,911
Mr Oxford, could you
spare a second over here?

364
00:36:26,218 --> 00:36:28,723
Rusk. It's Rusk!

365
00:36:28,897 --> 00:36:31,298
Hold him back. Where was this found?

366
00:36:31,472 --> 00:36:35,229
- Over at Henrietta Street.
- Any identification?

367
00:36:39,161 --> 00:36:41,527
Miss Barbara Milligan, Globe Public House.

368
00:36:41,701 --> 00:36:44,345
Covent Garden, London, WC2.

369
00:36:53,357 --> 00:36:55,444
(Clerk) Are you agreed upon your verdict?

370
00:36:55,618 --> 00:36:56,732
We are.

371
00:36:56,906 --> 00:36:59,306
Do you find the prisoner, Richard Ian Blaney,

372
00:36:59,515 --> 00:37:01,812
guilty or not guilty of the murder of Brenda...
(Fades Out)

373
00:37:19,974 --> 00:37:21,018
<i>...lan Blaney,</i>

374
00:37:21,191 --> 00:37:24,114
you have been found guilty
of a terrible crime.

375
00:37:24,288 --> 00:37:27,872
On its ghastly and wicked
nature I will not dwell.

376
00:37:28,046 --> 00:37:31,282
I only tell you that you must
entertain no expectation or hope

377
00:37:31,456 --> 00:37:34,865
that you will escape the consequences of it.

378
00:37:35,039 --> 00:37:39,667
The sentence of this court is that you
serve a term of life imprisonment,

379
00:37:39,841 --> 00:37:42,624
<i>for not less than 25 years.</i>

380
00:37:47,252 --> 00:37:50,209
(Blaney's Muffled Voice)
Rusk did it! I told you all along!

381
00:37:50,383 --> 00:37:51,427
<i>Rusk!</i>

382
00:37:51,601 --> 00:37:56,681
I keep telling you. Rusk, where are you?

383
00:37:56,855 --> 00:37:59,569
One of these days, you bastard!

384
00:37:59,743 --> 00:38:02,491
<i>Rusk, where are you? Rusk?</i>

385
00:38:02,665 --> 00:38:05,692
One of these days, I'm gonna get out
and kill you, you bastard!

386
00:38:05,866 --> 00:38:07,606
I've got nothing to lose now!

387
00:38:07,780 --> 00:38:10,285
I might as well do
what I'm being locked away for!

388
00:38:10,459 --> 00:38:12,929
You remember that! You remember that!

389
00:38:18,287 --> 00:38:20,375
<i>(Door Locks)</i>

390
00:38:40,242 --> 00:38:42,643
<i>(Blaney's Voice) Rusk did it.</i>

391
00:38:42,817 --> 00:38:46,261
<i>Rusk did it. I've told you all along!</i>

392
00:38:46,435 --> 00:38:49,288
<i>Rusk? Rusk, where are you?</i>

393
00:38:49,462 --> 00:38:52,802
<i>One of these days I’m gonna get out</i>
<i>and kill you, you bastard!</i>

394
00:38:53,011 --> 00:38:54,403
<i>I’ve got nothing to lose now.</i>

395
00:38:54,577 --> 00:38:57,430
<i>l might as well do what I’m being</i>
<i>put away for.</i>

396
00:38:57,569 --> 00:39:00,944
<i>You remember that! You remember that!</i>

397
00:39:13,087 --> 00:39:14,896
- Do you see the sign, Hartletts?
- Yes, sir.

398
00:39:15,070 --> 00:39:18,549
<i>(Oxford) It’s the fair-haired chap</i>
<i>in the brown suit underneath it.</i>

399
00:39:18,723 --> 00:39:20,115
- Did you see him?
- Yes, I did.

400
00:39:20,289 --> 00:39:24,116
We'll go around once again,
and I want a good, close mug shot.

401
00:39:24,986 --> 00:39:26,448
(Monica) Yes, Inspector, I remember him well.

402
00:39:26,621 --> 00:39:28,674
He came here on two or three occasions.

403
00:39:28,883 --> 00:39:32,328
Every business has its own
special cross to bear, I suppose.

404
00:39:32,536 --> 00:39:35,285
- And yours is men like this?
- That is so.

405
00:39:35,459 --> 00:39:38,799
Most of them are easy enough to get
rid of, but Mr Robinson here

406
00:39:38,973 --> 00:39:40,504
<i>was particularly insistent.</i>

407
00:39:40,678 --> 00:39:43,635
<i>- He wouldn't take no for an answer.</i>
- Mr Robinson?

408
00:39:43,809 --> 00:39:45,862
Yes, that is the man's name.

409
00:39:53,273 --> 00:39:54,526
<i>Here we are.</i>

410
00:39:54,700 --> 00:39:57,866
Mr William Robinson.

411
00:39:58,005 --> 00:40:02,598
You see, Inspector, he wanted us to
find women for him who enjoyed,

412
00:40:02,772 --> 00:40:05,799
well... certain peculiarities.

413
00:40:05,973 --> 00:40:09,522
Who were sexual masochists?
Who enjoyed being hurt?

414
00:40:09,696 --> 00:40:12,236
<i>- That sort of thing?</i>
- Quite.

415
00:40:12,410 --> 00:40:14,671
Perhaps you'd better see it for yourself.

416
00:40:14,845 --> 00:40:19,647
Naturally we told him we couldn't oblige,
but he kept coming back.

417
00:40:19,820 --> 00:40:20,934
Is it likely, do you think,

418
00:40:21,143 --> 00:40:24,657
that if Mr Robinson couldn't get
what he wanted from your agency,

419
00:40:24,831 --> 00:40:28,101
<i>- he would go to others?</i>
- Oh, yes, very likely.

420
00:40:28,275 --> 00:40:30,641
Men like this leave no stone unturned

421
00:40:30,815 --> 00:40:33,425
in their search for their
disgusting gratifications.

422
00:40:38,017 --> 00:40:39,757
Excuse me, Inspector.

423
00:40:39,931 --> 00:40:43,236
Do you have any special reason
for seeing Mr Robinson?

424
00:40:43,410 --> 00:40:48,316
Yes, Miss Barling. And I'd like you
to keep my visit confidential.

425
00:40:48,490 --> 00:40:50,578
Of course.

426
00:41:08,148 --> 00:41:11,628
<i>(Guard) Get the doctor quick.</i>
<i>Looks like an ambulance job.</i>

427
00:41:11,802 --> 00:41:13,889
(Sirens Wailing)

428
00:41:37,514 --> 00:41:40,924
I told you it wasn't Blaney, didn't I?

429
00:41:41,098 --> 00:41:44,160
I told you you were on the wrong track.

430
00:41:44,333 --> 00:41:48,265
A woman's intuition is worth more
than all those laboratories.

431
00:41:48,439 --> 00:41:51,292
I can't think why you don't
teach it in police colleges.

432
00:41:51,466 --> 00:41:54,215
So you think it's Rusk, do you?
You think he's our man?

433
00:41:54,389 --> 00:41:56,894
Well, of course. Anyone can see that.

434
00:41:57,068 --> 00:41:59,399
He knew both Mrs Blaney

435
00:41:59,573 --> 00:42:02,322
- and that Barbara what's-her-name.
- Yes.

436
00:42:02,496 --> 00:42:04,548
Well, there you are.

437
00:42:04,722 --> 00:42:06,984
You told me the man's a sexual pervert.

438
00:42:07,158 --> 00:42:10,429
That's why he kept the clothes
and put them in Mr Blaney's case.

439
00:42:10,602 --> 00:42:12,690
We have no proof of that.

440
00:42:12,864 --> 00:42:15,334
It stands to reason.

441
00:42:15,508 --> 00:42:17,561
Don't you mean intuition?

442
00:42:18,918 --> 00:42:22,154
What does your intuition tell you
I want for dinner tonight?

443
00:42:22,328 --> 00:42:24,833
Steak and a baked potato.

444
00:42:25,007 --> 00:42:30,400
But you're getting
pied de porc â la mode de Caens.

445
00:42:31,583 --> 00:42:34,123
<i>- (Oxford) It looks like a pig's foot!</i>
<i>- That's what it is.</i>

446
00:42:34,297 --> 00:42:38,402
I put it in the same sauce
the French use for tripe.

447
00:42:38,576 --> 00:42:40,629
That's comforting.

448
00:42:40,803 --> 00:42:43,030
Well, when are you going to arrest

449
00:42:43,204 --> 00:42:46,544
this Mr Robinson, or Rusk,
or whatever he's called?

450
00:42:46,683 --> 00:42:48,353
<i>When l have the proof l need.</i>

451
00:42:48,527 --> 00:42:53,572
<i>- It takes longer than intuition.</i>
<i>- When will you have it?</i>

452
00:42:54,233 --> 00:42:56,390
In a few minutes I hope, dear.

453
00:42:56,599 --> 00:42:58,826
Really?

454
00:42:59,000 --> 00:43:01,888
You old slyboots. Tell.

455
00:43:03,871 --> 00:43:06,307
Well...

456
00:43:11,839 --> 00:43:15,005
we know that if Rusk is the murderer,

457
00:43:15,179 --> 00:43:17,893
he traveled up in a potato truck
with his victim.

458
00:43:18,067 --> 00:43:19,876
How do we know that?

459
00:43:20,050 --> 00:43:23,912
Did you ever hear of a corpse
that cut itself out of a tied sack?

460
00:43:24,086 --> 00:43:27,739
<i>What would he want to take</i>
<i>the corpse out of the sack for?</i>

461
00:43:27,913 --> 00:43:30,001
Obviously he was looking for something.

462
00:43:30,175 --> 00:43:32,471
How do we know that?

463
00:43:32,680 --> 00:43:34,872
The corpse was deep in rigor mortis.

464
00:43:35,046 --> 00:43:38,664
He had to break the fingers of the
right hand to obtain what they held.

465
00:43:38,838 --> 00:43:40,926
(Cracking)

466
00:43:42,979 --> 00:43:45,936
It would be so nice to get back
to plain bread in this house.

467
00:43:46,110 --> 00:43:48,372
What do you think they held?

468
00:43:48,546 --> 00:43:51,851
A locket? A broach? A cross!

469
00:43:52,025 --> 00:43:54,982
It had to be something
that would incriminate him.

470
00:43:55,156 --> 00:43:58,079
Something that he missed
when he put the body on the truck.

471
00:43:58,218 --> 00:44:00,723
A monogrammed handkerchief, perhaps.

472
00:44:00,897 --> 00:44:02,985
Not a cross, I think.

473
00:44:03,159 --> 00:44:05,699
Well...

474
00:44:05,873 --> 00:44:08,169
I don't see why not.

475
00:44:08,308 --> 00:44:13,562
Religious and sexual mania are closely linked.

476
00:44:14,780 --> 00:44:18,329
Anyway, whatever it was, he found it,

477
00:44:18,503 --> 00:44:20,834
which was unlucky for us.

478
00:44:21,008 --> 00:44:25,044
But we did have one piece of good fortune.

479
00:44:25,218 --> 00:44:29,950
The truck driver told us that he
stopped at one place on his journey,

480
00:44:30,124 --> 00:44:33,429
and that was at a pull-in
somewhere out of London.

481
00:44:33,603 --> 00:44:35,238
- A pull-in?
- Hmm.

482
00:44:36,491 --> 00:44:41,118
It's a... cafe frequented by truck drivers, dear.

483
00:44:41,292 --> 00:44:44,807
They serve humble foods
like bacon and egg sandwiches,

484
00:44:44,981 --> 00:44:49,643
sausages and mashed potatoes
and cups of tea and coffee.

485
00:44:51,035 --> 00:44:53,714
How is it so fortunate
that this driver stopped there?

486
00:44:55,419 --> 00:44:57,123
It's not so much that he stopped,

487
00:44:57,297 --> 00:45:00,672
but that he stopped
only once that is important.

488
00:45:00,846 --> 00:45:03,908
The only place our man could've
got out of the truck was at that cafe.

489
00:45:04,082 --> 00:45:05,752
I sent Sergeant Spearman to see

490
00:45:05,926 --> 00:45:09,057
if he could find anyone who
could remember Rusk being there.

491
00:45:09,231 --> 00:45:12,050
I'm expecting him back at any minute.

492
00:45:12,224 --> 00:45:15,494
Well, eat up, dear. You'll want
to be finished by the time he arrives.

493
00:45:16,468 --> 00:45:19,008
Tasty, very tasty.

494
00:45:19,182 --> 00:45:21,653
Not a lot of meat on it, mind.

495
00:45:21,827 --> 00:45:23,427
No sense in gorging, dear.

496
00:45:23,601 --> 00:45:28,159
I'll take mine and eat it while I'm
beating my eggs for the soufflé.

497
00:45:28,333 --> 00:45:30,386
<i>(Doorbell Rings)</i>

498
00:45:33,900 --> 00:45:35,292
- Good evening, Sergeant.
- Good evening, sir.

499
00:45:35,466 --> 00:45:38,040
- Am I interrupting your dinner?
- No, not at all. Come in.

500
00:45:38,214 --> 00:45:40,824
- Thank you, sir.
- Put your hat and coat on the sofa.

501
00:45:43,607 --> 00:45:47,365
Good evening, Sergeant Spearman.
What would you like to drink?

502
00:45:47,539 --> 00:45:49,940
Good evening, madam. I don't know that I...

503
00:45:50,114 --> 00:45:51,819
Oh, that's alright. You're off duty.

504
00:45:51,958 --> 00:45:56,376
How about a Margarita? It's delicious.

505
00:45:56,550 --> 00:45:58,673
Tequila, triple sec,

506
00:45:58,847 --> 00:46:04,309
<i>fresh lemon juice and... salt</i>
<i>pressed 'round the rim of the glass.</i>

507
00:46:04,483 --> 00:46:06,954
<i>- You'll love it.</i>
- Thank you, madam.

508
00:46:10,990 --> 00:46:14,191
Sergeant Spearman, you are positively
glutinous with self-approbation.

509
00:46:14,365 --> 00:46:16,626
- You might as well speak out.
- Yes, sir.

510
00:46:16,800 --> 00:46:18,853
The woman behind the counter at the cafe

511
00:46:19,062 --> 00:46:21,845
positively identified Rusk
from the photo I showed her

512
00:46:22,019 --> 00:46:25,116
as being a man who was at the cafe
the night the body was discovered.

513
00:46:25,290 --> 00:46:27,099
And that's not all.

514
00:46:27,273 --> 00:46:31,622
- Are you waiting for a drumroll?
- No, sir. Sorry, sir.

515
00:46:31,796 --> 00:46:34,997
The woman also said that Rusk was
dishevelled and very dusty,

516
00:46:35,171 --> 00:46:38,476
and asked to borrow a clothes brush.

517
00:46:45,957 --> 00:46:48,184
This is the brush she lent him, sir.

518
00:46:48,358 --> 00:46:52,742
- You see there?
- (Sniffs)

519
00:46:52,916 --> 00:46:56,186
What do you say, Spearman? Potato dust?

520
00:46:57,404 --> 00:46:59,944
Here you are, Sergeant.

521
00:47:01,162 --> 00:47:02,762
Cheers.

522
00:47:02,936 --> 00:47:06,276
- Cheers, madam.
- Did you hear all that?

523
00:47:06,485 --> 00:47:10,869
<i>- Yes, l told you. l knew all the time.</i>
- (Oxford) Quite.

524
00:47:11,043 --> 00:47:14,522
- Get this down to the lab quickly.
- Very good, sir.

525
00:47:15,566 --> 00:47:18,350
It rather looks like we put
the wrong man away this time.

526
00:47:18,524 --> 00:47:22,386
What do you mean we? You put him away.

527
00:47:22,560 --> 00:47:25,413
- All right, Spearman, you can go.
- Good night, madam.

528
00:47:25,587 --> 00:47:26,943
You haven't finished your drink.

529
00:47:27,117 --> 00:47:30,318
I'm sorry. I have to get
down to the lab in a hurry.

530
00:47:30,492 --> 00:47:32,580
Good night, Spearman. Good work.

531
00:47:32,754 --> 00:47:34,807
- Very good work.
- Thank you, sir.

532
00:47:40,478 --> 00:47:45,210
Poor Mr Blaney. You've got
to get him out, Tim, immediately.

533
00:47:45,384 --> 00:47:47,576
He's in hospital at the moment.

534
00:47:47,750 --> 00:47:50,394
I'll talk to the assistant
commissioner in the morning

535
00:47:50,568 --> 00:47:51,925
and get the case reopened.

536
00:47:52,099 --> 00:47:55,613
He won't like it, but there's
quite enough evidence for a pardon.

537
00:47:55,787 --> 00:47:58,188
Will they give him any compensation?

538
00:47:58,362 --> 00:47:59,440
I expect they'll give him some money,

539
00:47:59,614 --> 00:48:03,685
but there's no real way
to compensate in cases like these.

540
00:48:03,859 --> 00:48:05,947
Poor man.

541
00:48:07,339 --> 00:48:12,036
I think the least you can do is ask
him 'round for a really good dinner.

542
00:48:12,836 --> 00:48:14,193
<i>Let's see.</i>

543
00:48:14,367 --> 00:48:17,533
<i>It will obviously have</i>
<i>to be something substantial.</i>

544
00:48:18,333 --> 00:48:23,448
I think a Caneton aux cerises.

545
00:48:24,457 --> 00:48:26,440
- What's that?
<i>- Duckling...</i>

546
00:48:26,579 --> 00:48:29,676
with heavy sweet cherry sauce.

547
00:48:31,311 --> 00:48:35,730
After that jail food he's been having,
I expect he'll eat anything.

548
00:48:42,375 --> 00:48:43,906
Excuse me.

549
00:48:44,080 --> 00:48:47,316
I must see if my soufflé's started to rise.

550
00:49:15,847 --> 00:49:18,839
Hey! Are the pills working?

551
00:49:27,816 --> 00:49:30,460
- He's sleeping like a baby.
- Do you think we gave him enough?

552
00:49:31,747 --> 00:49:33,243
Christ, mate, he's had half a dozen.

553
00:49:34,879 --> 00:49:37,592
Good. Now I'm off to get that bastard Rusk!

554
00:49:37,766 --> 00:49:39,784
Alright, alright. Let's make sure.

555
00:49:39,958 --> 00:49:42,916
It's now or never!
I'm due back inside tomorrow.

556
00:49:43,647 --> 00:49:44,760
George? George!

557
00:49:44,934 --> 00:49:47,335
<i>Alright, George?</i>

558
00:50:14,508 --> 00:50:17,883
Right, son, better be going.
Mind you do him up good.

559
00:50:18,057 --> 00:50:19,971
Here, take this strip of mica.

560
00:50:20,145 --> 00:50:23,137
You may need it to open his door.

561
00:50:26,929 --> 00:50:29,017
(Knocking)

562
00:50:41,612 --> 00:50:43,352
Doctor? Sister?

563
00:50:56,365 --> 00:50:58,000
Get a trolley, nurse.

564
00:51:05,411 --> 00:51:08,577
(Doctor) Sister, there seems to be
no evidence of a cerebral accident.

565
00:51:08,960 --> 00:51:11,256
<i>We'll have to admit him for observation</i>
<i>and then sort him out.</i>

566
00:51:11,604 --> 00:51:13,587
<i>(Nurse) Could he be an epileptic or diabetic?</i>

567
00:51:13,761 --> 00:51:16,023
<i>(Doctor) Not very likely in his sort of job.</i>

568
00:51:16,197 --> 00:51:18,980
<i>We're certainly going to need blood samples.</i>

569
00:51:26,774 --> 00:51:30,219
<i>Sleeping pills!</i>
<i>They've given him all their sleeping pills.</i>

570
00:51:39,474 --> 00:51:41,178
- Good night.
- Good night, sir.

571
00:52:28,045 --> 00:52:30,133
<i>(Alarm Ringing)</i>

572
00:52:33,612 --> 00:52:35,665
<i>(Alarm Continues)</i>

573
00:52:50,000 --> 00:52:52,087
(Engine Revving)

574
00:53:00,159 --> 00:53:02,247
<i>(Phone Ringing)</i>

575
00:53:03,395 --> 00:53:05,204
Hello?

576
00:53:05,831 --> 00:53:07,814
Good God! When was this?

577
00:53:07,988 --> 00:53:09,936
Right. What's that?

578
00:53:10,562 --> 00:53:13,033
Yes. Five minutes. I'll wait outside.

579
00:53:13,868 --> 00:53:17,208
I'm off! Blaney's escaped,
and I bet I know where he's gone.

580
00:53:20,513 --> 00:53:23,401
I often wondered whether Blaney
threw himself down those stairs

581
00:53:23,575 --> 00:53:25,941
in a suicide attempt,
or just as a means to get into the hospital.

582
00:53:26,115 --> 00:53:27,924
Now, of course, we have our answer.

583
00:56:22,830 --> 00:56:24,675
No. No!

584
00:56:24,848 --> 00:56:28,606
<i>- It’s not -</i>
- (Thumping Noise)

585
00:56:32,781 --> 00:56:35,356
<i>(Thumping Continues)</i>

586
00:56:58,041 --> 00:57:00,303
Mr Rusk.

587
00:57:00,894 --> 00:57:03,956
You're not wearing your tie.

588
00:57:05,000 --> 00:57:07,088
I -

589
